The sassor, naked from the shipwreck, seeks out a comrade stricken by the s‘ame blow to whom he may bewail his fate. The farmer who has lost his crops and the whole year’s fruits in the hail, weeps his sad lot on a bosom wounded like his own. Death draws the unhappy together; bereaved parents utter their groans with one voice, and the moment makes them equal. We too will strike the stars with words in unison; the saying is that prayers travel more strongly when united.

Believe me, 1 would love them all; but should you choose rather to come in person, lovely girl, you would beautify.your gist. Come, if you will, and lay sour apples to my tongue, the sharp flavour will be like honey as I bite.
